charismatic" versus "institutional" authority that have traditionally been used to distinguish the nature of episcopal authority from that of the ascetic and holy man. Instead she proposes a model of spiritual authority, ascetic authority and pragmatic authority, in which a bishop’s visible asceticism is taken as evidence of his spiritual powers and at the same time provides the justification for his public role. In clear and graceful prose, Rapp provides a wholly fresh analysis of the changing dynamics of social mobility as played out in episcopal appointments.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBishopszRome. 0aChurch historyyPrimitive and early church, ca. 30-600. 7aRELIGION / Antiquities & Archaeology.2bisacsh  aantiquity.  aascetic authority.  aascetic.  abible.  abishop.  achristian cult.  achristian rome.  achurch administration.  achurch hierarchy.  achurch history.  achurch leadership.  achurch officials.  achurch.  aconstantine.  aconversion.  aearly church.  aemperor.  aepiscopal authority.  ahistory of christianity.  ahistory.  aholy man.  aimperialism.  aleadership.  amonasticism.  amysticism.  anonfiction.  apatristics.  areligion.  areligious persecution.  aroman empire.  aspiritual authority.  aspiritual powers.  aspirituality.  astate religion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052028017540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093141140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520931411423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520931411/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY